n into the leafy, humid, forested landscapes of tropical Asia—the so-called tapovan, a Sanskrit word for the forest where knowledge is attained through tapasya, or inner struggle. Peter Ashton and David Lee, two of the world’s leading scholars on Asian tropical rain forests, reveal the geology and climate that have produced these unique forests, the diversity of species that inhabit them, the means by which rain forest tree species evolve to achieve unique ecological space, and the role of humans in modifying the landscapes over centuries. Following Peter Ashton’s extensive On the Forests of Tropical Asia, the first book to describe the forests of the entire tropical Asian region from India east to New Guinea, this new book provides a more condensed and updated overview of tropical Asian forests written accessibly for students as well as tropical forest biologists, ecologists, and conservation biologists.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aForest ecologyzAsia. 0aForest ecologyzTropics. 0aForests and forestryzAsia. 0aForests and forestryzTropics. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aforests, tropical, Asia, trees, diversity, evolution, climate change, deforestation.1 aLee, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076650940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226535722423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226535722/original  a978-3-11-076650-9  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles